t’s all a facade, a distraction so people can’t see that the girl is dead. She was gone, lying in the truck bed and she’ll never walk the ground of Glebe again as the same person. He took it away from her. <br /></p> <p>He was the good; Leon made her feel when she knew she shouldn’t. He was her light, though she wanted to keep him in the dark. </p> <p>Penny, who also goes missing, was the golden girl who left Romy consumed by hate and guilt. But Penny wanted her to step up because she could still report the crime, but is it a little too late? </p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"69b66e34b2fb6c9291f9d0470d3e5d1bb226ad24\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/69b66e34b2fb6c9291f9d0470d3e5d1bb226ad24/0_0_620_940/330.jpg\" alt=\"All the rage cover\" width=\"330\" height=\"500\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>By now, you may have guessed this story surrounds the sensitive issue of rape. Already starting at a low, the story remains in the same sort of atmosphere. It’s like floating in darkness, it’s lonely. That’s what made it such a difficult, long read. </p> <p>The negativity kept dragging me down to the point where I was exhausted, tired and physically strained worrying that Romy or any person was capable of that sort of dead emotion. It felt monotonous, repetitive and trapping. Yet I had to finish it. It’s one of those books that you can’t leave half completed, but can’t read in one sitting. </p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/jan/21/rape-culture-courtney-summers-tothegirls2016\">#ToTheGirls2016: Sometimes, saying a secret out loud changes a life</a> </p> </aside>  <p>Courtney Summers writes well and it is a great read despite her depressing words. </p> <p>“You know all the ways you can kill a girl?”; this book is one of them.</p